## `onnxruntime-web` peer dependency

The `@imgly` bundle does `import("onnxruntime-web")` for the CPU path and
`import("onnxruntime-web/webgpu")` for the WebGPU path at runtime. We
resolve both bare specifiers via the import map in `index.html`:

```html
<script type="importmap">
  {
    "imports": {
      "onnxruntime-web":        "/js/vendor/onnxruntime-web/ort.bundle.min.mjs",
      "onnxruntime-web/webgpu": "/js/vendor/onnxruntime-web/ort.webgpu.bundle.min.mjs"
    }
  }
</script>
```

The mapped files are `@imgly`'s pinned peer dep (currently `onnxruntime-web@1.21.0`,
MIT-licensed), vendored alongside this directory under
`js/vendor/onnxruntime-web/`. See `THIRD-PARTY.md` for the canonical entry.

### Browser compatibility

Import maps are baseline-supported in Chrome 89+, Firefox 108+, and Safari
16.4+. The site's stated browser support already requires ES2022 module
features, so this is well within scope. If a user on a stale browser hits
the bg-remove feature, the import will throw at first use and surface a
friendly toast (see `handleBgRemoveError` in `js/ops/bgremove.js`).

WebGPU is available in Chrome 113+, Edge 113+, and Firefox 121+ (behind a
flag at the time of writing). When `navigator.gpu` is absent, bgremove falls
back to the CPU path automatically — the user sees no difference beyond a
slightly slower run.

## Hosting requirements

The `npm run serve` script in this repo serves the right MIME types for
both `.wasm` and `.mjs`. For production on **GitHub Pages**, no extra
configuration is needed: GitHub Pages serves `.wasm` as
`application/wasm` and `.mjs` as `text/javascript` by default.

The site does NOT require cross-origin isolation (COOP/COEP). ORT Web will
fall back from threaded to single-threaded WASM when `crossOriginIsolated`
is false; we pay a small inference-time penalty in exchange for not having
to set unusual headers on a static host.

## Re-vendoring (bumping the upstream version)

```bash
# 1. Bump IMGLY_VERSION (and ORT_VERSION if @imgly's peer dep changed) in
#    scripts/install-bgremove.mjs.
# 2. Re-run:
node scripts/install-bgremove.mjs
# 3. Bump MODEL_HASH in js/ops/bgremove.js so previously-consented users
#    are re-prompted.
# 4. Bump the size line in THIRD-PARTY.md and re-verify
#    privacy.html's size claim.
# 5. Update the SHA-256 table above.
```

## Brand-stance compliance

At runtime, no third-party CDN is contacted. Every asset path lives under
`/js/vendor/bgremove/` or `/js/vendor/onnxruntime-web/`. This matches the
"ad-free, tracker-free, self-hosted" stance and the privacy panel's
disclosure. The 0-byte cost on initial page load is preserved because
`js/ops/bgremove.js` lazy-imports the bundle only on the first "Remove
background" click — the ~117 MB of chunks live in the repo but the browser
never fetches them until they're needed, then they're cached.
